[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] In DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, this pseudo-variable returns the last error level in a 3-digit format with leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] , this is a true environment variable automatically updated by the shell to the return code of exiting programs.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the 3-level day greeting time.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the hours of the current time in 12-hour format without leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the hours of the current time in 24-hour format in a 2-digit format with leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the months of the current date in a 2-digit format with leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the month name of the current date.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the number of day of the current week, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] login scripts, which may return versions also for non-DR-DOS versions of DOS.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the seconds of the current time in a 2-digit format with leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the year of the current date in a 2-digit format with leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] pseudo-variable returns the year of the current date in a 4-digit format, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the current number of screen columns depending on the display mode, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the days of the current date without leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the hours of the current time in 24-hour format without leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the months of the current date without leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the current number of screen rows depending on the display mode, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the seconds of the current time without leading zeros, f.e.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the user name.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] if the current drive is a PNW-mapped drive (otherwise an empty string is returned).
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] of the network adapter, but can be overridden.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the full name of the logged in user, if available.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] Indirectly, they are also supported under Windows' `COMMAND.COM`, which has been modified to internally call `CMD.EXE` to execute the commands.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable expands to the current date.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] External commands and some internal commands set error levels upon execution.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] This pseudo-variable returns the current time.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] The time is displayed according to the current user's time format preferences.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] variables are both used, it is important to read them both in this particular order in rapid succession in order to avoid midnight-rollover problems.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] Unix-like shells have similar dynamically generated variables, bash's `$RANDOM` being a well-known example.
[src:dotfiles-management/environment-variable-p02] However, since these shells have a concept of local variables, they are described as special local variables instead.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In computing, a **hidden file** or **hidden directory** is a file system object (such as a file or directory) that is excluded from a directory content report unless explicitly requested.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The value of hiding files is generally to avoid showing the user files that are not likely to be of interest to them.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The feature is not a security mechanism because access is not restricted; the user can request that normally-hidden files be displayed.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Hiding is a feature of the programs that display file system objects, not a feature of file systems or of the operating system as a whole.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The Unix-based `ls` shell command hides any file that starts with a dot (commonly called a **dot file** or **dotfile**) unless the option `-a` or `-A` is specified.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Even with wildcard matching, the command does not match a dotfile unless the expression starts with `.` For example, `*f*` does not match `.foo`, but `.f*` does.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In order to exclude those two entries from `ls` output, all entries prefixed with `.` were omitted.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] This meant that any file or directory could be excluded from the output of `ls` by giving it a file name with `.` as the first character.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Commonly, user-specific application configuration information is stored in the user's home directory as a dotfile.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Notable dotfiles include startup shell scripts such as `.profile`, `.login`, and `.cshrc` as well as `.plan` and `.project` which are used by the `finger` and `name` commands.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Many applications, from bash to desktop environments such as GNOME, store user-specific configuration this way, but the *XDG Base Directory Specification* aims to migrate such config files to be non-hidden (not starting with `.`) but stored in a hidden directory `$HOME/.config`.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The Android operating system provides empty .nomedia files as a hint to apps to exclude the content of the folder.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] This convention prevents photo and music files from appearing in picture galleries or played in MP3 player apps.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] This is useful to prevent downloaded voicemail files from playing between the songs in a playlist and to keep personal photos private while still allowing those in other folders to be shared freely.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] This convention is not enforced by the file or operating systems.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Each app is responsible for following the convention.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In the GNOME desktop environment (as well as programs using GLib), filenames listed in a file named .hidden are excluded from the directory containing the file.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In the file manager, keyboard shortcut Ctrl+H includes both dotfiles and files listed in .hidden.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In addition to the dotfile behaviour, files with the invisible attribute are excluded by Finder although not by `ls`.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The invisible attribute can be set or cleared via the `SetFile` command.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] For example, command line `SetFile -a V jimbo` hides the file jimbo.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Starting in Snow Leopard, the `chflags` command can also be used.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] For example, `chflags hidden jimbo` is equivalent.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The FAT, NTFS, and ReFS file systems, which have originated from DOS and Windows, maintain two file attributes called "hidden" and "system" for each item.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] In Windows Command Prompt, the `dir` command excludes items that have either the "hidden" or "system" attributes.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] If invoked with the `/a` command-line switch, the command shows all items, even the hidden ones.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Its variations `/as` and `/ah` respectively display files with the "system" and "hidden" attributes.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The `attrib.exe` command-line utility, included will all versions of MS-DOS and Windows, can set or clear attributes.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] File Explorer controls visibility based on user settings that are accessible from its toolbar (or via the Control Panel).
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] By Default, File Explorer excludes items with the "hidden" attribute, but can reveal them if the "Show hidden files, folders, or drives" is set.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Items with the "System" attribute remain hidden unless another setting, called "Hide protected operating system files (Recommended)," is cleared.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] File Explorer renders the icons of hidden items semi-transparently.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] A Windows Shell hack allows one to hide the content of a folder by suffixing a pre-defined CLSID to its name.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The folder is still visible in File Explorer, but its content becomes one of the Windows special folders.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] This hack is restricted to File Explorer and Windows Shell API.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] Any app that doesn't use the Shell API (including the bundled Windows Command Prompt and PowerShell) can see the folder, its name, and its content.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] PowerShell started out as the successor Windows Command Prompt for Microsoft Windows, but is now a cross-platform, free, and open-source shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The `Get-ChildItem` cmdlet, by default, doesn't display hidden items, unless configured to do so via parameters.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] With the `-Force` parameter, the cmdlet displays all items, including hidden ones.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] With the `-Hidden` parameter, the cmdlet displays only hidden items, excluding ordinary items.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The cmdlet also features a `-Attributes` parameters that allows granular filtering by specific attributes.
[src:dotfiles-management/hidden-file-and-hidden-directory] The `Get-ItemProperty` and `Set-ItemProperty` cmdlets can query or modify the `Attributes` property of each file or directory.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] A **home directory** is a file system directory on a multi-user operating system containing files for a given user of the system.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The specifics of the home directory (such as its name and location) are defined by the operating system involved; for example, Linux / BSD (FHS) systems use `/home/⟨username⟩` or `/usr/home/⟨username⟩`, macOS uses `/Users/⟨username⟩`, and Windows systems since Windows Vista use `\Users\⟨username⟩`.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] A user's home directory is intended to contain that user's files; including text documents, music, pictures, videos, etc.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] It may also include their configuration files of preferred settings for any software they have used there and might have tailored to their liking: web browser bookmarks, favorite desktop wallpaper and themes, stored passwords to any external services accessed via a given software, etc.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The user can install executable software in this directory, but it will only be available to users with permission to execute files in this directory.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The home directory can be organized further with the use of sub-directories.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The content of a user's home directory is protected by file-system permissions, and by default is accessible to all authenticated users and administrators.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] Any other user that has been granted administrator privileges has authority to access any protected location on the file system including other users' home directories.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] Separating user data from system-wide data avoids redundancy (the same system files can be used by between different users) and makes backups of files that are important for a specific user simpler.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] In most operating systems, the superuser usually have a different location for the home directory than regular users.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The superuser is usually *root* in Unix-like systems, and *SYSTEM* in Windows NT.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The file `/etc/xdg/user-dirs.defaults` on many Linux systems defines the subdirectories created for users by default.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] Creation is normally done with the first login by Xdg-user-dirs, a tool to help manage "well known" user directories like *desktop*, *downloads*, *documents*, *pictures*, *videos*, or *music*.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The tool is also capable of localization (i.e. translation) of the folders' names.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] In Unix, the working directory is automatically set to a user's home directory when they log in.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] In many built-in commands, typing the `~` (tilde) character is equivalent to specifying the current user's home directory.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The Unix superuser has access to all directories on the file system, and hence can access home directories of all users.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] The superuser's home directory on older systems was /, but on many newer systems it is located at /root (Linux, BSD), or /var/root (macOS).
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] In the OpenVMS operating system, a user's home directory is called the *root directory*, and the equivalent of a Unix/DOS/Windows/AmigaOS *root directory* is referred to as the *Master File Directory*.
[src:dotfiles-management/home-directory] Single-user operating systems simply have a single directory or partition for all user files, there is no individual directory setup per user (though users can still setup and maintain directories inside this main working directory manually).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In computing, a **symbolic link** (a.k.a.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] **symlink** or **soft link**) is a special computer file that refers to another file or directory by storing a path to it, thus providing an alternative access path without duplicating the target's content.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Apps that use operating system services may treat a symbolic link like other files or directories, and would not know that it is a symbolic link unless they investigate its nature.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] A symbolic link will break if its target is moved or deleted.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Symbolic links are supported in Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, although they impose varying limitations on them.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Alternatives to symbolic links include hard links, shortcut files, and Windows shell objects.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] A symbolic link is an independent file that stores a file system path that, except for special situations, is treated as the file system item to which the path refers: the *target*.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] If a symbolic link is deleted, its target is not affected.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] If the target is moved, renamed or deleted, the symbolic link is not automatically updated or deleted.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Its target path would point to nothing and might be described as *broken*, *orphaned*, *dead*, or *dangling*.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The symbolic link differs from the hard link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The latter cannot link to a target on a different volume or file system, but the former can.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] A hard link always refers to an existing target, whereas a symbolic link might be a path to nothing.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Symbolic links were introduced in 1982 in 4.1a BSD Unix.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The POSIX standard defines the symbolic link as found in most Unix-like operating systems, such as FreeBSD, Linux, and macOS.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] CTSS on IBM 7090 supported files linked by name in 1963.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] By 1978, some symbolic links were supported in minicomputer operating systems from DEC, and Data General's RDOS.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Symbolic links may be implemented in a context-dependent or variable fashion, such that the link points to varying targets depending on a configuration parameter, run-time parameter, or other instantaneous condition.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] A *variable* or *variant symbolic link* has a variable name (such as username of environment specific info) embedded in its path definition, allowing some flexibility that is not possible with a standard symbolic link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] NetBSD, DragonFly BSD, and Domain/OS support such links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Tru64 uses a *context dependent symbolic link* where the context is the cluster member number.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Pyramid Technology's OSx operating system supports *conditional symbolic links*.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The aforesaid context-dependent symbolic links serve to restructure the file system hierarchy, allow for a more intuitive or application-specific directory structure, and to reorganize the file system without redesigning core system functions and utilities.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Because of its nature, the symbolic link feature causes a hierarchical file system to be a directed graph instead of a tree, which can affect otherwise simple operations.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] For example, navigating to a directory's parent may not work reliably with symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Some Unix shells heuristically try to uphold the illusion of a tree-shaped hierarchy, but this causes them to produce different results compared to other programs that manipulate paths without such heuristics, relying on the operating system instead.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows 95 also had a similar intuitiveness concern, but instead of adopting symbolic links, created the Windows shell, special folders, and shortcut files (see § Alternatives for details).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In a Unix-like OS, the `ln` shell command can create either a hard link (via the `link()` API function ) or a symbolic link (via the `symlink()` function).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Ideally, the target should exist, although a symbolic link may be created to a non-existent target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The following example creates an empty file called "foo", then creates a symbolic link called "bar" that points to "foo".
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Most operations treat a link as an alias for the target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] For example, shell commands that access file content access the content of the target file.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] But file management operations may operate on the link or the target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The `lstat()`, `lchown()` and `readlink()` APIs apply directly to the link file, not their targets.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] An app (e.g., `ls` or `find`) can use `lstat()` rather than `stat()` to distinguish and report on symbolic links instead of their targets.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Because the `rename()` and `unlink()` API functions are coded to operate on symbolic links, the `rm` and `mv` commands (which use these APIs) affect the symbolic link itself.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The `cp` command has options that allow either the symbolic link or the target to be copied.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The `ls -l` command can reveal a symbolic link's target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The output shows the link's name, followed by a `->` mark and the link's target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In this example, `ls` reveals the symbolic link that the previous example created.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Early implementations stored the link path in a regular file.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The file contained the target path as text, and the file mode bits marked the file as a symbolic link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The reported size of such a symbolic link is the number of characters in the path it points to.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The file system permissions of a symbolic link are not used; the access modes of the target file are controlled by the target file's own permissions.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] To enhance storage space and performance, the *fast symlink* allowed storage of the target path within the data structures used for storing file information on disk (inodes).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] This space stores a list of disk block addresses allocated to a file.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Thus, symbolic links with short target paths are accessed quickly.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Systems with fast symlinks often fall back to using the original method if the target path exceeds the available inode space.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The original style was retroactively termed a *slow symlink*.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] It is also used for disk compatibility with other or older versions of operating systems.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Only when a link points to a file in the same directory do "fast symlinks" provide significantly better performance than other symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Dangling symlinks are intentionally created by systemd as key-value data storage when the value is small enough.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The symlink name is the key, the target path is the value.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The rationale is that, instead of 2 system calls for read and 3 system calls for write, it would only take 1 system call to read and 2 system calls for write.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Microsoft Windows support symbolic links in the NTFS and ReFS file systems, as well as the Windows kernel namespace.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Starting with Windows 2000, NTFS supports junction points, also known as soft links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Junction points are similar to symbolic links, but only link to other directories, not files.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] They are implemented via NTFS reparse points.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows 7 and Vista support a maximum of 31 reparse points for a given path (i.e. any given path can have at most 31 redirections before Windows gives up).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Also starting with 2000, NTFS supports volume mount points.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Normally, Windows volumes are assigned a drive letter.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Volume mount points act like a symbolic link to the root of another volume that is not assigned a drive letter.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] NTFS version 3.1 introduced support for symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows XP partially implemented NTFS 3.1, leaving out symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Thus, a third-party driver is required to enable support for NTFS symbolic links in Windows XP.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows Vista and later enabled support for symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Unlike NTFS junction points, a symbolic link can also point to a file or remote Server Message Block (SMB) network path.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Additionally, the NTFS symbolic link implementation provides full support for cross-volume links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] However, the functionality enabling cross-host symbolic links requires that the remote system to also support them.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Symbolic links are designed to aid in migration and application compatibility with POSIX operating systems.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Microsoft aimed for Windows Vista's symbolic links to "function just like UNIX links".
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] To create a symbolic link, the user account must possess the new *"*Create Symbolic Link" privilege (`SeCreateSymbolicLinkPrivilege`), which, by default, only admins have.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In Windows Vista and later, when the working directory path ends with a symbolic link, the current parent path reference, `..`, will refer to the parent directory of the symbolic link rather than that of its target.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Users could use Command Prompt or PowerShell to create symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The following creates a symbolic link called "Downloads" at "`E:\`" that points to the Downloads folder in the user's profile.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] This works in Command Prompt only as `mklink` is a built-in shell command.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The `/D` switch in this command requests a junction point instead of a file symbolic link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] This command succeeds even if the target doesn't exist.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Unlike Command Prompt, PowerShell returns an error if the source object path is invalid.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In exchange, PowerShell correctly determines the type of the source object and creates the right type of symbolic link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In addition to file and folders, NTFS symbolic links can point to an alternate data stream.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The following example creates a symbolic link called "`Test.txt`" that points the "`Zone.Identifier:$DATA`" alternative stream of a file called "`npcap-1.83.exe`".
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The low-function responsible for creating symbolic links is the `CreateSymbolicLink()` function of Windows API, introduced in 2008.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] It can create both file and directory symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Much later, in 2021, Microsoft introduced `File.CreateSymbolicLink()` and `Directory.CreateSymbolicLink()` methods to .NET 6.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Cygwin simulates POSIX-conforming symbolic links in the Windows file system.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] It uses identical programming and user utility interfaces as Unix (see above), but creates Windows shortcuts (.lnk files) with additional information used by Cygwin at the time of symbolic link resolution.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Cygwin symbolic links comply with the POSIX standard in terms of how they are resolved, and with Windows standards in terms of their on-disk representation.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Additionally, Cygwin can be set up to support native Windows symbolic links which can be used out of Cygwin without restrictions.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Cygwin has no way to specify shortcut-related information – such as working directory or icon – as there is no place for such parameters in `ln -s` command.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] To create standard Microsoft .lnk files Cygwin provides the `mkshortcut` and `readshortcut` utilities.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The Cygwin User's Guide has more information on this topic.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] MSYS2, which is based on Cygwin, has a similar set of winsymlinks settings but defaults to copying the files.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The following table compares various aspects of the symbolic link (both UNIX-based and Windows), junction point (NTFS) and hard link (UNIX-based).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The Windows implementation is not POSIX-conforming.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Creating them requires the "create symbolic link" privilege (`SeCreateSymbolicLinkPrivilege`).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] By default a user account holds this privilege when it is either an administrator or has Developer Mode enabled (Windows 10 v1703 and later).
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] POSIX permits a hard link to a directory but does not require the capability.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Modern file systems tend to not support it.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Implementations of features similar to symbolic links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] 1963 and Incompatible Timesharing System both have linked files where the name of the target file is specified in a directory entry.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Data General's RDOS for its Nova computers supports "link entries", which are directory entries that contain both the name of the entry and the name of another file, so that a reference to a file using the name of the entry refers to the other file.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The command creating symbolic links is `makelink`, which is also used for hard links.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Internally the dos.library returns an error code indicating that a target is a soft link if you try to perform actions on it that are only legal for a file, and applications that wish to follow the symbolic link then needs to explicitly make a call to follow the link and retry the operation.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The AmigaDOS shell will follow links automatically.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In the classic Mac OS, applications or users can use *aliases*, which, unlike symbolic links, follow the target, even if it is moved to another location on the same volume.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] macOS also supports aliases; they are not supported by Unix APIs such as `open()`, but are supported by Carbon and Cocoa higher-level APIs.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] In the OS/2 operating system, symbolic links somewhat resemble shadows in the graphical Workplace Shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] However, shadows, due to the fully object-oriented System Object Model, are considerably more powerful and robust than a simple link.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] For example, shadows do not lose their capabilities when renamed or when either the object or subject of the link is relocated.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Shortcuts, which are supported by the graphical file browsers of some operating systems, may resemble symbolic links but differ in a number of important ways.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The Windows shell allows ordinary directories on file systems to act as "junction points".
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] They are transparent to the Windows shell, but useless in other environments.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows offers two methods to implement a folder shortcut.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The first is through a special naming convention.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The folder shortcut must be adhere to the following syntax: `Name.{CLSID}`.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Windows shell will replace the entire name with the associated CLSID's display name.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The *shell objects* or *shell folders* are defined in the Windows Registry and can be used to implement a sort of symbolic link too.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] Like folder shortcuts, they are transparent to the Windows shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/symbolic-link] The *My Documents* folder on the *Desktop* as well as the *Fonts* and the *Administrative Tools* folders in the *Control Panel* are examples of *shell objects* redirected to file-system folders.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A **Unix shell** is a shell that provides a command-line user interface for a Unix-like operating system.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A Unix shell provides a command language that can be used either interactively or for writing a shell script.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A user typically works within a Unix shell via a terminal emulator; however, direct access via serial hardware connections or a Secure Shell are common for server systems.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Although use of a Unix shell is popular with some users, others prefer to use a graphical shell in a windowing system, such as those provided in desktop Linux distributions or macOS, instead of a command-line interface (CLI).
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A user may have access to multiple Unix shells with one configured to run by default when the user logs in interactively.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The default selection is typically stored in a user's profile (for example, in the local passwd file or in a distributed configuration system such as NIS or LDAP).
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A user may use other shells nested inside the default shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] A Unix shell may provide many features including: variable definition and substitution, command substitution, filename wildcarding, stream piping, control flow structures (condition-testing and iteration), working directory context, and here document.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The first Unix shell was the Thompson shell, *sh*, written by Ken Thompson at Bell Labs and distributed with Versions 1 through 6 of Unix, from 1971 to 1975.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Though rudimentary by modern standards, it introduced many of the basic features common to all later Unix shells, including piping, simple control structures using `if` and `goto`, and filename GLOBbing.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Though not in current use, it is still available as part of some Ancient UNIX systems, such as Version 6 Unix.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] It was modeled after the Multics shell, developed in 1965 by American software engineer Glenda Schroeder.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Schroeder's Multics shell was itself modeled after the RUNCOM program Louis Pouzin showed to the Multics Team.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The "rc" suffix on some Unix configuration files (e.g.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] ".bashrc" or ".vimrc"), is a remnant of the RUNCOM ancestry of Unix shells.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The PWB shell or Mashey shell, *sh*, was an upward-compatible version of the Thompson shell, augmented by John Mashey and others and distributed with the Programmer's Workbench UNIX, circa 1975–1977.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] It focused on making shell programming practical, especially in large shared computing centers.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] It added shell variables (precursors of environment variables, including the search path mechanism that evolved into $PATH), user-executable shell scripts, and interrupt-handling.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Control structures were extended from if/goto to if/then/else/endif, switch/breaksw/endsw, and while/end/break/continue.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] As shell programming became widespread, these external commands were incorporated into the shell itself for performance.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] But the most widely distributed and influential of the early Unix shells were the Bourne shell and the C shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Both shells have been used as the coding base and model for many derivative and work-alike shells with extended feature sets.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The Bourne shell, *sh*, was a new Unix shell by Stephen Bourne at Bell Labs.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Distributed as the shell for UNIX Version 7 in 1979, it introduced the rest of the basic features considered common to all the later Unix shells, including here documents, command substitution, more generic variables and more extensive builtin control structures.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The language, including the use of a reversed keyword to mark the end of a block, was influenced by ALGOL 68.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Traditionally, the Bourne shell program name is sh and its path in the Unix file system hierarchy is /bin/sh.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] But a number of compatible work-alikes are also available with various improvements and additional features.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The POSIX standard specifies its standard shell as a strict subset of the Korn shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] From a user's perspective the Bourne shell was immediately recognized when active by its characteristic default command line prompt character, the dollar sign ($).
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The C shell, *csh*, was modeled on the C programming language, including the control structures and the expression grammar.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] It was written by Bill Joy as a graduate student at University of California, Berkeley, and was widely distributed with BSD Unix.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The C shell also introduced many features for interactive work, including the history and editing mechanisms, aliases, directory stacks, tilde notation, cdpath, job control and path hashing.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] On many systems, csh may be a symbolic link or hard link to TENEX C shell (tcsh), an improved version of Joy's original version.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Although the interactive features of csh have been copied to most other shells, the language structure has not been widely copied.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The only work-alike is Hamilton C shell, written by Nicole Hamilton, first distributed on OS/2 in 1988 and on Windows since 1992.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Shells read configuration files in various circumstances.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] These files usually contain commands for the shell and are executed when loaded; they are usually used to set important variables used to find executables, like $PATH, and others that control the behavior and appearance of the shell.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] The table in this section shows the configuration files for popular shells.
[src:dotfiles-management/unix-shell] Same behavior as sh, but only if invoked as sh (bash 2+) or, since bash 4.2, also if invoked *explicitly* in POSIX compatibility mode (with options --posix or -o posix).
